title: For Sale:  Martini Enfield .303
postcontent: I'm selling my Martini Enfield .303 conversion. The original gun was built in 1885, chambered in .450/577. Then, after England adopted the Lee Metford (and then Lee Enfield) in .303, large numbers of these Marini Henrys were sent out the colonies for their colonial troops to carry. This particular gun was sent to Egypt, along with conversion parts, and was converted in 1904 in their Citadel Armory. This is an actual Martini Enfield, converted from a real Martini Henry, using English made parts, under supervision of English armorers in Egypt. This isn't a Khyber Pass copy. The gun shows it's age (all 131 years of it), but still shoots just fine. The action works smoothly. It is missing the cleaning rod. The only real issue is that there is a crack in the forearm around a pin, just ahead of the receiver. This can be repaired if you know what you are doing (I don't, for the record), or you can actually buy new made stocks for these old warhorses and put the originals away somewhere. I would recommend shooting lower power commercial or reloads on this gun. The Martini actions are strong, but some of the military surplus, made for machineguns in World Ward II is probably a little too hot for a girl this old. Matching bayonets can found pretty readily online (typically around $100 to $150), also made by Citadel.

title: For Sale:  Belgian "RIC" Genredes Revolvers Americaine revolver
postcontent: I'm selling a Belgian revolver, made most likely in the 1880's. It is a copy of a Webley RIC revolver and appears to be in .44 S&W Russian (at least it says 44 on the side and those rounds chamber just fine in the cylinder, so that's my guess on the caliber). The cylinder has a bit of a wobble when the hammer is cocked, but locks fairly tight when the hammer drops. Otherwise, like a lot of other revolvers of the time, it spins freely. The safety works when the hammer is down, preventing the gun from being cocked. Like the Webley it is copied from, while it is a double action revolver, it has a loading gate and rounds are loaded and empty shells are ejected one at a time (if you have shot a Nagant revolver, it's the same loading procedure). The top of the gun says Genredes Revolvers Americaine, but whether that's the model, I don't know. I haven't been able to find much information about this gun, which really isn't unusual for Belgian revolvers of the era.I might be interested in some trades, mostly pocket pistols from the early 20th century (mostly in .25 auto or .380, like Berettas, Astras, Colts, etc... no modern junk please) and possibly some older revolvers in .38 S&W, .38 Special, or .32 S&W or S&W Long (like a Colt Police Positive or S&W 1903 to fill some holes in my collection)

title: For Sale:   Trocaola Aranzabal y Cia Smith Express revolver
postcontent: This is a Spanish made, Trocaola Aranzabal y Cia Smith Express revolver. This gun is a 10 shot revolver chambered in .32 S&W Long. It is double action only, with a shrouded hammer. It also has an external safety, which works. The gun is a top break with an ejector similar to top break S&Ws or Webleys. The gun was nickel plated, but that finish is a bit rough. It was likely made sometime between World War I and World War II (possibly for the Spanish Civil War, which consumed a lot of Spains weapons output). As you can see, someone has crudely scratched what I assume their initials in it, RL. Whether this was done in 1936 or the week before I picked it up earlier this year, I have no idea. I'd like to think some Republican soldado did it while he was bored in between fights with Franco's fascists, but I don't think we'll ever know for sure. The gun's inner works seem to function, though it is loose. However, the firing pin has the tip worn down or broken off, so it won't actually ignite a primer. This could be fixed if you wanted to, if you can find a gunsmith able to work on odd guns and maybe fabricate some of their own parts.
